column16:
What's your home address?
If you are not comfortable of providing the accurate location, you don’t have to give your exact address. Just something nearby is great — like a street corner, the name of a shop, or your building (no unit number needed). Anywhere within 50 meters of your home works!
column17:
Scenario 1.1
Policy Description:
Allow 4–6 story buildings (65 ft max) at the key intersections or transit hubs shown in orange, and lift unit-count limits there. 

Everyday Framing:
In each orange-shaded intersection on the map, you’d see new 4–6 story apartment buildings—some units set aside as affordable housing, ground-floor shops or services, and high-quality, context-sensitive design helping spread new homes and jobs fairly across the city.

Over the past five years, my housing experience in San Francisco has focused on preparing for and adapting to family life. I live with my husband and our two young kids, currently 1 and 3 years old. We’ve been able to maintain a stable rental situation, though space and affordability are always on our minds.

Before having kids, we lived in a smaller apartment, which worked fine for just the two of us. But when we found out we were expecting our first child in 2022, we decided to move into a larger rental in a quieter, more family-friendly neighborhood. We wanted a place with nearby parks, good childcare options, and enough room for our growing family.

While we didn't have to navigate newborns during the height of the pandemic, the lasting effects—like rising costs and limited housing options—have definitely shaped our decisions. Buying a home in the city still feels financially out of reach, but we’re focused on stability, and making sure our kids have a safe and comfortable environment to grow up in.

column4: I have lived in the same flat for over 30 years as I have rent control. My landlord has wanted me out since he bought the building.  During the pandemic he did illegal construction in the building as everyone moved out except me. My building was built in the 1930s. I got very sick and was diagnosed with lead exposure. I had the apartment tested which cost 1800$ that I never got back as my landlord would do nothing to help me. It turns out the amount of lead in the hallway was 10x the amount allowed safe by the EPA. There were other rooms that had an unsafe amount of lead also. There is no law in SF that forces a landlord to do anything to fix your apartment if you get sick from lead. Lead is not taken seriously in this city  like it is in places such as New York. Since my experience I have heard of other people in SF getting lead exposure in their apartment. Only if there are children present will it be illegal .  This law has to change. I lost a lot of weight and felt like I was going insane, there were no services available . Luckily I had good insurance to be able to see an environmental specialist. When one of the building inspectors came, It took 2 months for the building inspector to post his findings. My landlord had to hire someone to redo all the floors and repaint most of the rooms. It took 6 months . He dragged it out, hoping I would move. I could not live in my apartment the whole time. My landlord did not reimburse me for any of this. After hiring an independent inspector who tested the house and agreed it was safe I was finally able to move back in. The landlord had other violations which were all reduced by the other inspectors. The other inspectors had told me there were grave violations, however, after speaking with my landlords reps barely anything was done about those.

column4: Over the past five years in San Francisco, I have experienced several changes in my housing situation. I initially lived in a shared apartment in the Mission District, renting a room with roommates to keep costs manageable. After two years, I moved to a studio in the Inner Richmond for more privacy, as my work situation stabilized and I could afford a higher rent. In 2022, due to a rent increase and the expiration of a rent-controlled lease, I relocated to a one-bedroom unit in the Sunset District. Most of my moves were driven by affordability, job changes, and the desire for a quieter or more spacious living environment.

column4:
My housing journey has been a bit of a classic San Francisco tale. I initially landed in a somewhat cramped but charming studio in the Inner Sunset five years ago. It was a rental, and while I loved being close to Golden Gate Park and the vibrant Irving Street, the lack of space started to feel restrictive as my needs grew. The rent was also, predictably, quite high and seemed to creep up a little each year.
About three years ago, I decided to look for something a bit bigger and, perhaps, slightly more affordable I ended up moving to a one-bedroom apartment in the Outer Sunset. It was further from the main action, but the apartment was significantly larger, and having more space was a real plus.
